4 2:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=993.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   What It Is About</span><hr size=1> These are the points: <br>
1. George Bush the Second started a war in Afghanistan and Iraq. <br>
2. This war has given him immense popularity. <br>
3. The immense popularity must be upheld by his support group if they are to maintain their current power status. <br>
4. Wars are costly and create large deficits. <br>
5. This is one of the biggest attack points for anyone trying to take down Bush. <br>
6. A space program is costly, but can be justified by factoids about Velcro. Much of these advances were merely popularized and advanced by the space program. <br>
7. A boost to the manned launch section of the space program is a reasonable investment to achieve even greater popularity and cancel out the attack points of a huge and growing deficit. <br>
8. So Bush's popularity would increase just as crunch time is coming for election, at the very time which Bush the First's popularity was decreasing after Gulf War I. <br>
9. An upgrade to the manned launch section of the space program, Cold War style, would detriment the cost of launch because the vast amount of money offers itself to reckless, &quot;1000 dollar toilet seat&quot; spending. Cost-Plus Contracts (vs. Fixed-Price Contracts) operate by paying the contractor for cost and a percentage of the cost. Thus, there is no impetus to drive down costs, and an opposite incentive to increase them.<br>
10. It would also rip away growing investor confidence in the small-scale suborbital passenger and microsatellite launch markets. Why invest in these companies if NASA is doing it anyway, the investors will ask. <br>
11. These small companies, which can only survive by driving down costs will be delivered a potential death blow by this type of government spending. <br>
12. With the lack of an equivalently strong Cold War opponent, or at least the perception of one by the public, the boost to the manned flight space program will wither away into paper studies and balsa wood models, or at best, result in a vehicle that is as dangerous and inefficient as Shuttle because of the requirement that it must use new and untried technologies, and serve every possible payload requirement by every possible customer. <br>
<br>
Conclusion: <br>
A boost to the manned flight space program has very little chance of success of putting humans and business into space in a permanent, significant way. It will also be detrimental to those businesses which would drive down the costs of launch, and create reasonably cheap access to space. <br>
<br>
I would like to see humans get into space. I would like to go there myself and intend to. However, I would like to see it done not in the right/wrong/government/not-government way, but the cheap and affordable &quot;I could pay for that&quot; way. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cotopaxi@nuclearspace>cotopaxi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 163<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/16/04 1:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=993.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What It Is About</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I would like to see it done not in the right/wrong/government/not-government way, but the cheap and affordable &quot;I could pay for that&quot; way. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
